Testing Final

UDEP Project, Brigham Young University

1. Poverty

Income

The overall average income per day is $1.2870883^{5}.

The average income per day for men is $6.56, and the average income per day for women is $5.0547928^{5}. However, the difference is not significant.

The average income per day for the population ages 0 to 40 is $3.3293802^{5}, and the average income per day for adults is $ 4.23. However, the difference is not significant.

Access to Facilities

In this sample, 47.68% of the participants have access to electricity or energy, 49.38% of the participants have access to water and sanitation, and 49.21% of the participants have access to refuse and waste removal.

Land Ownership

50.49% of all the participants own land. 49.56% of men in the sample own land and 52.97% of women in the sample own land. However, the difference in land ownership between men and women is not significant.

Additionally, 12.66% of the participants who indicated they own land also have legal documentation that proves the land ownership. 11.88% of men and 11.3% of women in this smaller sample have the legal documentation. However, the difference in legal documentation given land ownership between men and women is not significant.

Comparisons to other Households

Participants were asked to imagine that all the households in their community are on a step on a ladder, from 1 to 9, where 9 indicates the richest households on the top step, and 1 indicates the poorest households on the bottom step. The average response was 2 and the distribution was positively skewed.

When asked to compare their household’s access to basic services (critical services including electricity and energy, water and sanitation, refuse and waste removal) to other households in the community 0% said they had less basic services than most households, 32% said they had about the same amount of basic services as most households, and 33% said they had more basic services than most households.

Participants were also asked to imagine that all the households in their community are on a step on a ladder, from 1 to 9, where 9 indicates the households that are most able to buy land on the top step, and 1 indicates the households that are least able to buy land on the bottom step. The average response was 2 and the distribution was negatively skewed.

2. Hunger

At some point in the past 12 months, 47.17% of the participants have worried about having enough food, 50.37% have been unable to eat nutritious food, and 49.14% have only able to eat a few kinds of food.

Additionally, in the past 12 months, 49.39% of the participants had to skip a meal, 51.46% ate less than they should, and 48.75% ran out of food, all because they did not have enough money.

Finally, in the past 12 months, 50% of the participants were hungry at some point but did not eat and 49.88% went hungry for an entire day.

Comparison to other Households

When asked to compare their household’s amount of food to eat to other households in the community 32% said they had less food to eat than most households, 35% said they had about the same amount of food to eat as most households, and 33% said they had more food to eat than most households.

When asked to compare the health of the children in their household to that of other children, 0% of participants said they had less food to eat than most households, 0% said they had about the same amount of food to eat as most households, and 0% said they had more food to eat than most households.

3. Healthy Lives

Fertility and Maternal Health

In the past 12 months, 52.58% of all participants have given birth, and 33.33% of 15-19 year olds have given birth. 0.08% of women who gave birth had the birth attended by skilled staff.

Health Care Access

50.91% of the partcipants know of access to substance abuse treatment, 46.53% have access to health coverage, and 34.63% have current health insurance.

48.89% can afford the medicine their family needs, 48.89% can provide medicine when their family needs it, and 51.52has an access to prescription medicines.

Additionally, 49.69% of the participants have access to vaccinations, 49.56% can afford vaccinations, and 34.96% have received vaccinations.

Comparison to other Households

Participants were asked to imagine that all the women in their community are on a step on a ladder, from 1 to 9, where 9 indicates the women who are healthiest on the top step, and 1 indicates the women who are the least healthy on the bottom step. The average response was 2 and the distribution was negatively skewed.

When asked to compare their household’s support needed for a healthy birth to other households in the community 3% said they had less support needed for a healthy birth than most households, 2% said they had about the same support needed for a healthy birth as most households, and 4% said they had better support needed for a healthy birth than most households.

Participants were also asked to imagine that all the households in their community are on a step on a ladder, from 1 to 9, where 9 indicates the healthiest newborns on the top step, and 1 indicates the least healthy newborns on the bottom step. The average response was 2 and the distribution was normal.

4. Quality Education

Education

91.1% of households have somebody with at least some grade school completed.
When asked to compare the most educated person in their household to other members of the community, 31% said they had less education than members of the community, 34% said they had about the same amount education as most households, and 34% said they had more formal education than others.


91.4% of respondents have at least some some grade school completed(91.9% of men and 92.5% of women).

75% of all the participants have participated in education or vocational training in the past 12 months. 66.7% of men in the sample have participated and 75% of women in the sample have participated. However, the difference in education/training participation between men and women is not significant.

Of the women in the sample, 75% are or were enrolled in college, university, or trade school, 0% are or were enrolled in technical or vocational training, and 0% are or were enrolled in grade school.

Of the men in the sample, 66.7% are or were enrolled in college, university, or trade school, 0% are or were enrolled in technical or vocational training (TVET), and 0% are or were enrolled in grade school.

Computer Activities

Of the following nine computer skills, the average number that each household possesses is 5.4.

  • 61.6% of respondents live with someone able to copy or move a file or folder.
  • 58.1% of respondents live with someone able to use copy and paste tools to duplicate or move information within a document.
  • 57.4% of respondents live with someone able to send e-mails with attached files (e.g. document, picture, video).
  • 58.2% of respondents live with someone able to use basic arithmetic formulae in a spreadsheet.
  • 59.2% of respondents live with someone able to connect and install new devices (e.g. a modem, camera, printer).
  • 60.5% of respondents live with someone able to find, download, install, and configure software.
  • 61.1% of respondents live with someone able to create electronic presentations with presentation software (including text, images, sound, video or charts).
  • 58.3% of respondents live with someone able to transfer files between a computer and other devices.
  • 62.1% of respondents live with someone able to Writing a computer program using a specialized programming language.

When asked to compare their household’s technology skills to those of other members of the community, 35% said they had fewer technology skills than other households, 0% said they had about the about the same amount of technology skills as other households, and 0% said they had more technology skills than other households.

5. Gender Equality

52.1% of respondents in the sample are married or joined in a union. 48.5% of respondents own a mobile phone (45.5% of men and 51.5% of women). Of those with a mobile phone, 46.9% have internet access through their mobile phone.

Unpaid labor and leadership

98.5% of households have a woman in a management position.

The average amount of unpaid labor per week (such as caregiving, cleaning, errands for the household, and home maintenance) is 73.3 (72.7 for men; 73.9 for women). The difference between men and women’s hours of unpaid labor is not statistically significant.

Amount of unpaid labor compared to other women and men in community

Physical, Sexual, and Psychological Violence

In the last 12 months, 100% of married female respondents 15 years and older reported that a household member had been a victim of physical, sexual, or psychological violence. On a scale of 1-9, with 9 being most safe from violence and 1 being least safe, respondents rate their household a 2.7 on average. The distribution is negatively skewed.

49.7% of respondents with women in their household indicate that any women or girls in their household have undergone female genital mutilation or cutting. Of the households who have women that have undergone genital mutilation, the average number of women who have experienced this is 52. 30% of respondents with women in their household believe that their household has a higher percentage of women who have experienced female genital mutilation or cutting than most households, 33.7% believe their household is about the same as other households, and 36.3% believe their household has a lower rate of female genital mutilation or cutting than most households.

Land ownership

33.7% of female respondents or respondents who reside with a woman feel that the women in their household own about the same amount of property or land as most women in other households within their community, 32.4% feel women in their household own less, and 33.9% feel women in their household own more.

Among households in which a woman resides, 99% have at least one woman who owns agricultural land. Among households in which at least one woman owns agricultural land, the average number of women who own agrictultural land is 51.2149123.

Reproductive Health and Decision Making

51.3% of respondents know of services that can help them regarding decisions of their sexual relations including contraceptive use and reproductive health. Of those respondents who know of services,36.6% have access to those services.

18.2% of women aged 15-49 always feel like they are in control of decisions regarding their sexual relations including contraceptive use and reproductive health.

Women are most likely to report having the same amount of control over decisions affecting their reproductive health compared to most women .

6. Clean Water and Sanitation

When asked about how frequently a household members had to drink water they felt was unsafe 21% said never, 20% said rarely (1-2 times in the prior 4 weeks), 18% said sometimes (3-10 times in the prior 4 weeks), 20% said often (11-20 times in the prior 4 weeks), and 20% said always (above 20 times in prior 4 weeks).

When asked about what water sources they had access to 62% of participants said they had access to piped water into their dwelling, yard or plot, 64% said they had access to public taps or standpipes, 64% said they had access to boreholes or tubewells, 62% said they had access to protected dug wells, and 64% said they had access to protected springs and rainwater.

When asked about restroom facilities 48% said they had access to a flush or pour flush toilet to a sewer system with just hand sanitizer. 33% said they had access to a flush or pour flush toilet to a sewer system with soap and water. The rest of participants either did not respond or used another form of restroom with less access to sanitation.

When asked to compare their access to sanitary facilities to other households in the community, 35% said they had worse access to sanitary facilities than most households, 0% said they had about the same access to sanitary facilities as most households, and 0% said they had better access to sanitary facilities tha nmost households.

When asked to compare their access to clean drinking water to other households in the community, 34% said they had worse access to clean water than most households, 0% said they had about the same access to clean drinking water as most households, and 0% said they had better access to sanitary facilities than most households.

7. Affordable and Clean Energy

Of those who reported having access to electricity 290.32 people out of 1000 had access to a national grid connection, 265.51 people out of 1000 had access to a local mini grid connection, 278.74 people out of 1000 had access to an electric generator, 278.74 people out of 1000 had access to a rechargable battery, 283.71 people out of 1000 had access to a dry-cell battery, 272.95 people out of 1000 had access to a solar lantern, 259.72 people out of 1000 had access to a solar multi-light product, 291.98 people out of 1000 had a solar home system, 272.13 people out of 1000 had access to pico-hydro electricity, and 0 people out of 1000 responded that they don’t know, and 258.89 people out of 1000 responded “Other”.

When asked about primary fuel source for cooking 20% of participants said traditional (such as dung, agricultural residue, and fuelwood), 18% said intermediate (such as charcoal and kerosene), and 19% said modern (such as LPG, Biogas, ethanol gas, plant oils, dimethyl ether (DME), and electricity).

When asked about primary fuel source for heating 17% of participants said traditional (such as dung, agricultural residue, and fuelwood), 20% said intermediate (such as charcoal and kerosene), and 21% said modern (such as LPG, Biogas, ethanol gas, plant oils, dimethyl ether (DME), and electricity).

When asked about primary fuel source lighting 19% of participants said traditional (such as dung, agricultural residue, and fuelwood), 20% said intermediate (such as charcoal and kerosene), and 21% said modern (such as LPG, Biogas, ethanol gas, plant oils, dimethyl ether (DME), and electricity).

Of those who have access to electricity 0% use electricity mainly for appliances (includes refrigerator, dishwasher, clothes washer and dryer), 33% mainly use it for cooking, 0% mainly use it for entertainment and electronics (includes external power adapters, TVs, home office equipment, computers, and small appliances), 33% mainly use it for heating, and 33% mainly use it for lighting.

On average famalies use electricity 12 hours a day. Households also on average lose electricty 50 times a week. The average length of a power outage is 51 hours.

When asked to compare thier home’s access to electricity to other households in the community 32% said they had a home with worse access to electricity than most households, 34% said they had a home with about the same access to electricity as most households, and 33% said they had a home with Better access to electricity than most households.

8. Decent Work and Economic Growth

Hourly Wage Differences

Of all participants 69% are employed. Of those who are employed 25% work in local organizations, 25% are self-employed, 26% work for multinational organizations, and 24% work for the government.

Females make on average NaN dollars an hour in local organizations, 2 if self-employed, 3 in multinational organizations, and 3 in government organizations. Males make on average 2 dollars an hour in local organizations, 1 if self-employed, 1 in multinational organizations, and 2 in government organizations. However, the difference in hourly wage between men and women is not significant.

Females 40 years old and under make on average 1 dollars an hour, while those above 40 make . However, the difference in hourly wage between women above and below 40 is not significant. Men 40 years old and under make on average 2 dollars an hour, while those above 40 make 2. Also, the difference in hourly wage between men above and below 40 is not significant.

Females that are disabled make on average 3 dollars an hour, while those who are not make . However, the difference in hourly wage between women that are and are not disabled is not significant. Men that are disabled make on average 1 dollars an hour while those who are not make 2. However, the difference in hourly wage between men that are and are not disabled is not significant.

Workplace Safety and Household Injuries

Of all participants 33% were in households where someone was injured within the last twelve months. 31.88% of men and 34.25% of women were in households where someone was injured in the last twelve months. However, the difference in household injuries between men and women is not significant.

Access to Banking and Finacial Services

Of all participants above the age of 15, 100% have access to a bank, mobile money account, banking/Micro finance account, or loans. 32% have had someone in their household within the past 12 months that made a financial transaction using a mobile phone.

Participants were asked to compare one member of their household with other members of the community in regards to hazardous jobs. When asked to make this comparison, 33% said the member of their household had less hazardous working conditions than others in the community, 34% said the member of their household had working conditions that were about as hazardous as others in the community, and 32% said the member of their household had more hazardous working conditions than others in the community.

When asked to compare their household’s access to financial services to other households in the community 31% said they had worse access to financial services than most households, 34% said they had about the same access to financial services as most households, and 35% said they had better access to financial services than most households.

9. Reduced Inequalities

Of all participants 25% do not have a place to call home. Of those who have a home 25% have a home that is missing one or more walls or roof and has a dirt floor, 26% have a home that includes temporary walls or roof and has a dirt floor, 25% have a home with solid walls and floor.

When asked what describes their home 28% of participants said my home is too small for my family’s needs, 24% said my home is big enough for my family’s needs, 24% said my home is too big for my family’s needs.

When asked to compare thier home to other households in the community 31% said they had a home less nice than most homes, 34% said they had a home about the same as most homes, and 35% said they had a home nicer than most homes.
